							<h1>Midautumn Festival</h1>

                            <p>
                                <br>
                                The Mid-Autumn Festival is a longstanding Chinese tradition that has been celebrated since the Shang Dynasty. The festival celebrates the end of the harvest, as well as having strong associations with the moon. Legend has it that there were once ten suns that scorched the earth at all times. To solve this problem, the Emperor of Heaven had the great archer, Hou Yi, shoot down nine of these suns. To reward him for this, the emperor gave Hou Yi an elixir of immortality. Not wanting to live forever without his beautiful wife, Chang’e, he instead hid the elixir in his home. Unfortunately, on the 15th day of the eighth month, while Hou Yi was out hunting, his apprentice, Feng Meng, went to his home to steal the elixir for himself. To prevent him from stealing it, Chang’e took the elixir herself, becoming immortal and ascending to the moon as its goddess, leaving Hou Yi alone on earth. When he learned of this he was heartbroken and left fruits and cakes in their yard as an offering to the moon. Soon others learned of his story and started leaving food out too on the 15th day of the eighth month to honor her. 
                                <br> <br />
                                Many families celebrate this holiday in different ways but for the people of Chinatown in Chicago it is a community wide celebration that brings the community together as a whole. One major way that the community celebrates the festival is through mooncakes, a dense pastry shaped like the moon to honor Chang’e. These come in a wide variety of flavors but the most common are red bean, lotus paste, and five kernels, some of which contain egg yolks to represent the phases of the moon. In the afternoons, a variety of traditional Chinese shows and performances can be viewed. These shows range from traditional lion dancing or fan dancing, to a Qipao fashion show. For the 2019 Mid-Autumn Festival, 12 artists created paintings of the different animals of the zodiac assigned to them. For the Chicago Chinatown community, The Mid-Autumn Festival is a unifying element and a reminder of Chinese traditions.
                            </p>
								
